1.  Don't place a feeder in the direct sun - the nectar will become way too hot.  (Flowers naturally cool the nectar.)

2.  Don't hang a feeder under a canopy or awning - the birds can (and often times do) fly up under the covering and become disoriented and will die from exhaustion while trying to escape. 

3.  Hanging a feeder from the very edge of an awning, etc. is OK - the birds will clear the potential trap as they leave the feeder.

4.  Boil nectar water to drive off the chlorine.  Otherwise the birds may wait an extended period for the chlorine to naturally gas off.  DON"T color the water - that's useless and potentially harmful.

5.  Keep nectar at the ready in the fridge and change it often (once a day) in hot weather.  Place only the amount necessary for the day in the feeder.  But you must be strategic about the timing - they don't want the stuff cold any more than they want it hot, and they feed constantly from daylight to dark.  Toggle feeders if you must to accommodate.

6.  Smell the nectar in the feeder if it remains there 2-3 days in hot weather, and you'll appreciate why it's important to change it often.  Would you want to drink that?

7.  Wasps can be a hassle.  Keep the outside of the feeder clean of nectar to help deter.
